      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that <m>|z| = 1</m> if and only if <m>\frac 1 z = \overline{z}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>z</m> is a real number if and only if <m>z = \o z</m>;
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>z</m> is either real or purely imaginary if and only if <m>(\o{z})^2 = z^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_alg">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove <xref ref="alg">Proposition</xref>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that if <m>z_1 \, z_2 = 0</m> then <m>z_1 = 0</m> or <m>z_2 = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_easyexp">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove <xref ref="easyexp">Proposition</xref>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_rootofunity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix a positive integer <m>n</m>.
        Prove that the solutions to the equation <m>z^n = 1</m> are precisely
        <m>z = e^{ 2 \pi i \frac m n }</m> where <m>m \in \Z</m>.
        (<em>Hint</em>: To show that every solution of <m>z^n = 1</m> is of this form,
        first prove that it must be of the form
        <m>z = e^{ 2 \pi i \frac a n }</m> for some <m>a \in \R</m>,
        then write <m>a = m + b</m> for some integer <m>m</m> and some real number <m>0 \le b \lt 1</m>,
        and then argue that <m>b</m> has to be zero.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_5throotsof1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that
        <me>
          z^5 - 1 \= \left( z-1 \right) \left( z^2 + 2z \cos \tfrac{ \pi }{ 5 } + 1 \right) \left( z^2 - 2z \cos \tfrac{ 2 \pi }{ 5 } + 1 \right)
        </me>
        and deduce from this closed formulas for
        <m>\cos \frac{ \pi }{ 5 }</m> and <m>\cos \frac{ 2 \pi }{ 5 }</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix a positive integer <m>n</m> and a complex number <m>w</m>.
        Find all solutions to <m>z^n = w</m>.
        (<em>Hint</em>: Write <m>w</m> in terms of polar coordinates.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use <xref ref="easyexp">Proposition</xref>
        to derive the triple angle formulas:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos (3 \phi) = \cos^3 \phi - 3 \cos \phi \sin^2 \phi</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin (3 \phi) = 3 \cos^2 \phi \sin \phi - \sin^3 \phi</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_Casmatrices">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given <m>x, y \in \R</m>,
        define the matrix <m>M(x,y) := \displaystyle\begin{bmatrix}x \amp  -y \\ y \amp  x \end{bmatrix}</m>.
        Show that
        <me>
          M(x,y) + M(a,b) \ = \ M(x+a, \, y+b) \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad M(x,y) \, M(a,b) \ = \ M(xa-yb, \, xb+ya) \,
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        (This means that the set <m>\{ M(x,y) : \, x, y \in \R \}</m>,
        equipped with the usual addition and multiplication of matrices,
        behaves exactly like <m>\C = \{ (x,y) : \, x,y \in \R \}</m>.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_conjugation">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove <xref ref="conjugation">Proposition</xref>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Sketch the following sets in the complex plane:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \left| z - 1 + i \right| = 2 \right\}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \left| z - 1 + i \right| \leq 2 \right\}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \Re (z+2-2i) = 3 \right\}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \left| z - i \right| + \left| z + i \right| = 3 \right\}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, |z| = |z + 1| \right \}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, |z-1| = 2 \, |z + 1| \right \}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \Re(z^2) = 1 \right \}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\left\{ z \in \C : \, \Im(z^2) = 1 \right \}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="realpolynomialb">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>p</m> is a polynomial
            <idx><h>polynomial</h></idx>
        with real coefficients.
        Prove that
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\o{p(z)} = p \left( \o z \right)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>p(z) = 0</m> if and only if <m>p \left( \o z \right) = 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_reversetriangle">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove the reverse triangle inequality<idx><h>reverse triangle inequality</h></idx>
        (<xref ref="cor_triangleineq">Proposition</xref>
        <xref ref="revtrianineq"></xref>)
        <m>\left| z_1 - z_2 \right| \geq \left| z_1 \right| - \left| z_2 \right| </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use the previous exercise to show that
        <me>
          \left| \frac{1}{z^2 - 1} \right| \leq \frac{1}{3}
        </me>
        for every <m>z</m> on the circle <m>C[0,2]</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Sketch the sets defined by the following constraints and determine whether they are open, closed,
        or neither; bounded; connected.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\abs{z+3}\lt 2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\abs{\Im(z)}\lt 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>0\lt \abs{z-1}\lt 2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\abs{z-1}+\abs{z+1}=2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\abs{z-1}+\abs{z+1}\lt 3</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\abs{z} \ge \Re(z) + 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What are the boundaries of the sets in the previous exercise?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G</m> be the set of points
        <m>z \in \C</m> satisfying either <m>z</m> is real and <m>-2\lt z\lt -1</m>,
        or <m>|z|\lt 1</m>, or <m>z=1</m> or <m>z=2</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Sketch the set <m>G</m>,
              being careful to indicate exactly the points that are in <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine the interior points of <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine the boundary points of <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine the isolated points of <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The set <m>G</m> in the previous exercise can be written in three different ways as the union of two disjoint nonempty separated subsets.
        Describe them,
        and in each case say briefly why the subsets are separated.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that the union of two regions with nonempty intersection is itself a region.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that if <m>A \subseteq B</m> and <m>B</m> is closed,
        then <m>\partial A \subseteq B</m>.
        Similarly, if <m>A \subseteq B</m> and <m>A</m> is open,
        show that <m>A</m> is contained in the interior of <m>B</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_parametrizations">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find a parametrization for each of the following paths:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              the circle <m>C[1+i, 1]</m>, oriented counter-clockwise
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              the line segment from <m>-1-i</m> to <m>2i</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              the top half of the circle <m>C[0, 34]</m>, oriented clockwise
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              the rectangle with vertices <m>\pm 1 \pm 2i</m>,
              oriented counter-clockwise
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              the ellipse <m>\{ z \in \C : \, |z-1| + |z+1| = 4 \}</m>,
              oriented counter-clockwise
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_diamondpath">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Draw the path parametrized by
        <me>
          \gg(t) = \cos(t) \left| \cos(t) \right| + i \sin(t) \left| \sin(t) \right| , \qquad 0 \le t \le 2 \pi \,
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G</m> be the annulus determined by the inequalities <m>2\lt \abs z\lt 3</m>.
        This is a connected open set.
        Find the maximum number of horizontal and vertical segments in <m>G</m> needed to connect two points of<nbsp/><m>G</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
